    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Diagnostics Model Years 1999-2000 - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEM DIAGNOSTICS -
        Circuit Function And Diagnostics - Vehicle Speed Sensor Signal (VSS)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
        <title>Vehicle Speed Sensor Signal (VSS)</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Signal Function</title>
            <figure id="f17503109" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg1/eg1257.png" type="png" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for Vehicle Speed Sensor</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Transmission tailshaft speed is detected by a magnetic pickup mounted on the transmission that senses
                the rotation of a 16 tooth gear installed on the rear of the transmission. This alternating current (AC)
                sine wave signal is received by the ECM and used with tire size and axle ratio, to calculate vehicle
                speed. Calculated vehicle speed is transmitted to the instrument cluster on the American Trucking
                Association (ATA) data link to operate the speedometer in the instrument cluster. Calculated vehicle
                speed is also used in the control strategies that control features such as Cruise Control, PTO operation
                and Road Speed Limiting.
            </para>
            <para>WTEC MD transmissions use an internal VSS sensor to signal the WTEC ECM. The WTEC ECM buffers the
                signal and sends a square wave signal to the Engine ECM.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            <para>When the ECM determines that the vehicle is operating at 0 MPH, the ECM performs diagnostic checks on
                the VSS circuit. A voltage signal transmitted by the ECM will detect if the return voltage is Out of
                Range High or Out of Range Low. An Out of Range Low Diagnostic Trouble Code normally indicates an open
                or short to ground. An Out of Range High Diagnostic Trouble Code normally indicates a short to voltage.
                When a VSS Diagnostic Trouble Code is detected, the ECM disables Cruise Control, PTO operation. If Road
                Speed Limiting is enabled, it will limit engine rpm in all gears.
            </para>
            <para>For vehicles equipped with Allison MD (WTEC) transmissions, Diagnostic Trouble Codes are not sent for
                VSS circuit failures. Any VSS Diagnostic Trouble Codes set with MD transmissions diagnose the
                communication circuit between the Engine ECM and the Transmission ECM.
                <emph type="bold">See Allison WTEC maintenance/diagnostic manual to diagnose any MD VSS sensor
                    problems.
                </emph>
            </para>
